\begin_layout Paragraph
Starting from Coulomb's Law show that the potential function for a uniformly
 charged sphere is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(r\right)=-\frac{Ze^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}R}\left(\frac{3}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{r}{R}\right)^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the charge radius of the sphere.
 Find the difference between this potential function and a point like nucleus
 on the energy of an electron in the ground state electron wave function
 from the hydrogen atom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coulomb's Law gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

To determine the potential, we must integrate over a spherical volume element,
 giving us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int F_{C}dV & =\int\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}dV\\
 & =\int_{0}^{2\pi}\int_{0}^{\pi}\int_{R}^{r}\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}\sin\phi r^{2}drd\phi d\theta\\
 & =\int_{R}^{r}\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}Ze\cdot edr\\
 & =\frac{Ze^{2}}{2\pi\epsilon_{0}}\int_{R}^{r}dr\\
 & =\frac{Ze^{2}}{2\pi\epsilon_{0}}\left[r-R\right]+c_{1}\\
 & =\frac{Ze^{2}}{2\pi\epsilon_{0}R}\left[\frac{r}{R}-1\right]+c_{1}\\
 & =-\frac{Ze^{2}}{2\pi\epsilon_{0}R}\left[1-\frac{r}{R}\right]+c_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we know that when 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R$
\end_inset

, the potential function is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(r\right)=-\frac{Ze^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{1}=-\frac{Ze^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and finally
\end_layout

