\begin_layout Paragraph
The wave function of the two-nucleon state may be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{total}=\Phi_{total}\alpha_{spin}\chi_{isospin}
\]

\end_inset

In this case we consider the proton and neutron to be identical particles
 with just different projections in isospin space.
 This leads to the extended Pauli Exclusion Principle that two nucleons
 must have an overall wave function that is anti-symmetric w.r.t.
 interchange of the two particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Discuss the space part of the wave function and symbolically write out the
 spatial wave function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space part of the wave function for a spherical potential can be written
 as the spherical harmonics discussed above, which provide a function for
 the polar and azimuthal angular dependence.
 There will also be a radial dimensionality, which is probably related to
 the potential, but at this level of abstraction, we cannot say much more
 about it.
 This function, by applying parity transformations to it, is symmetrical.
 Thus, symbolically, we can write this function as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{total}=\mathscr{R}\left(r\right)Y_{lm}\left(\theta,\varphi\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Discuss the spin part of the wave function and symbolically write out the
 spin wave function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spin wave function compared between the two particles, a proton and
 a neutron, is symmetric.
 This function is the sum of the quarks in the neutron and proton, the neutron
 having 
\begin_inset Formula $udd$
\end_inset

 and the proton having 
\begin_inset Formula $uud$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the third component of the spin vector is the only requirement here,
 and as such, our spin can be written as only a function of this factor.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{spin}=\mathscr{S}\left(s_{z}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Given our knowledge of the space and spin of the deuteron what must the
 symmetry of the isospin wave function be? Write explicitly the isospin
 wave function of the deuteron.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symmetry must be antisymmetric because of the symmetry of the spin and
 spatial wavefunctions, to garner a totally asymmetric wave function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{total}$
\end_inset

.
 The isospin wave function can be found by the four additions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|p,n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 These states are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|p,n\right\rangle =\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle ,\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle ,\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle ,\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

And we need to then normalize these to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
N^{2}\left|p,n\right\rangle ^{2} & =N^{2}\left(\left\langle \downarrow\uparrow\right|+\left\langle \uparrow\downarrow\right|\right)\left(\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)=1\\
 & =N^{2}\left(1+0+0+1\right)=1\\
 & N^{2}=\frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So then, with our normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\nicefrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 and in one dimension using the possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq m\leq1$
\end_inset

, we have a triplet state (with 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)\\
\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle 
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

and a single state of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)
\]

\end_inset

Unfortunately, two of the states of the triplet state (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

) cannot exist (two protons or two neutrons cannot be bound).
 Thus, the entire triplet state cannot exist.
 Then, the singlet state must exist, and the property of the singlet state,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

 is that it is antisymmetric.
 We can prove it's antisymmetry by applying parity to it
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathscr{P}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)\right) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(-\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)\\
 & =-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

